AGI -&nbsp;The "peaceful analytes" broken by hatred and wars, "the rubber walls of selfishness and indifference" that prevent the construction of the most just city, the sufferings that leave "uncolmable empties", the fears that prevent us from doing good. These are some "signs of death", the tombstones present in our heart that steal the force of moving forward.&nbsp;Papa&nbsp;Francesco, in the homily of the Easter Vigil of the Holy Night, which they have assisted in the Basilica of St. Peter 6,000 faithful,&nbsp; taking the passage of the Gospel, the women who go to the Sepulchre and the Easter announcement First women wonder who will roll the stone away; Then, looking up, they see that it has already been rolled." "First of all - the Pontiff has explained - there is the question that assillates their heart broken by the pain: who will roll away the stone from the tomb? That stone was the end of Jesus' story buried in the night of death. He, the life coming into the world, was killed; He, who manifested the merciful love of the Father, did not receive mercy; He, who raised sinners from the weight of the condemnation, was condemned to the cross. The Prince of Peace, who had liberated an adulterer from the violent fury of the stones, lies buried behind a large stone. That rock, insurmountable obstacle, was the symbol of what women brought into their hearts, the corner of their hope: against it everything had broken, with the dark mystery of a tragic pain that had prevented their dreams to come true." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Brothers and sisters, this can also happen to us - Francis added -. Sometimes we feel that a tombstone was heavily rested at the entrance of our heart, suffocating life, extinguishing trust, imprisoning us in the tomb of fears and bitterness, blocking the way to joy and hope. They are 'evils of death' and we meet them, along the way, in all those experiences and situations that steal the enthusiasm and the strength to move forward: in the sufferings that touch us and in the dead of the loved ones, who leave in us unknowing empties; we meet them in the failures and fears that prevent us from fulfilling what good we have at heart; We find them in all the closures that restrain our gnashings of generosity and do not allow us to open ourselves to love; we find them in the rubber walls of selfishness - they are real rubber walls - and indifference, which reject the commitment to build cities and societies more just and to measure of man; We find them in all the desires of peace broken by the cruelty of hatred and the ferocity of war." "When we experience these disappointments, we have the feeling that so many dreams are destined to be broken and we also ask ourselves distressed: who will break the stone from the tomb?" Yet, he continued the &nbsp;Papa, "the same women who had the darkness in the heart testify to us something extraordinary: When they looked up, they observed that the stone was already rolled, but it was very big." "Behold the Passover of Christ, behold the strength of God: the victory of life on death, the triumph of light on darkness, the rebirth of hope within the rubble of failure. It is the Lord, God of the impossible that, forever, has rolled away the stone and began to open our tombs, so that hope does not end. Towards him, then, we must also look up." &nbsp;

